Done. I ran 12 iterations of propose-test-refine analysis on the 50,000-patient prostate cancer dataset and emitted both `transcript.json` (validates against the schema) and `analysis_summary.txt`.

**Key finding:** `treatment_enzalutamide` is the only treatment with a meaningful effect on `objective_response`, and that effect is concentrated in a precise 4-variable subgroup:

> **mcrpc=0 AND ar_v7_positive=0 AND brca2_mutation=0 AND msi_high=0** (n=15,681, 31% of cohort)
> Inside: rr=0.80 on enzalutamide vs 0.17 off (diff +0.63, p≈0)
> Outside: diff +0.008 (p=0.05)

Notable null/negative findings worth flagging:
- The expected biomarker-targeted pairings did **not** replicate: pembrolizumab × MSI-H (no effect), lu177-PSMA × PSMA-high (no effect), olaparib × BRCA2 (borderline **negative**, adjusted p=0.058 — opposite of the standard expectation).
- Treatment assignment is balanced across all measured covariates, supporting causal interpretation.
